---
title: "How to Build Process Habits That Outlast the People Who Created Them"
date: "2024-11-05"
summary: "Build process habits that survive personnel changes. Document the habit and enforce it with the system."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Habit Systems"
author: "Redevise"
---

Your best operations person created a habit. They check every new process step before it goes live. They left. The habit left with them.

A process habit that depends on a specific person is not a habit. It is a person. When the person leaves, the habit dies.

Here is how to build habits that outlast people.

Document the habit. Write down what the person does. Not in a paragraph. In a checklist. The checklist is the habit in written form.

Enforce the habit with the system. The system requires the checklist to be completed before the process goes live. Not a person. The system.

Train the next person. The next person follows the checklist. The system enforces the sequence. The habit continues.

I documented a process habit for a client in 2024. The habit was held by one person. We wrote a checklist. We built the checklist into the system. The person left three months later. The habit continued. The system enforced it.

The teams that depend on people are the ones that lose habits when people leave. The teams that depend on systems are the ones that keep habits when people leave.

Document the habit. Enforce with the system. Train the next person. The habit outlasts.
